vectorData.altText: That's right! The greater palatine nerve (C), a branch of the maxillary division of the trigeminal nerve (V2), innervates the hard palate.

Identify the hard and soft palates

Review its innervation on the specimen:
Like almost all structures inferior to the eyes and superior to the oral fissure, the general sensory innervation to the palate comes from branches of the maxillary nerve, V2. 
The greater (A) and lesser (B) palatine branches of the maxillary nerve reach the palate from the pterygopalatine fossa (C) by descending through the palatine canal to emerge through the greater (C) and lesser (D) palatine foramina in the palatine bone. The nasopalatine branch of the maxillary nerve (E) reaches the anterior part of the palate from the nasal septum, by passing through the incisive canal (F). 
Blood supply to the palate is from the palatine branches of the maxillary artery (G) which travel with the palatine nerves.
